{"cursor":"4372","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox pro football player |image= |birth_date= |birth_place=Childress, Texas\n|death_date= |college=Tulsa |position=Linebacker |NFLDraftedYear=1947\n|NFLDraftedRound=12 / Pick 104 (by the New York Giants) |PreAFLProBowls=1952\n|DatabaseFootball=BROWNHAR01 |PFR=BrowHa00 |NFL=BRO469200 |years=1948 1949 1950 1950 1951-\n1955 1956 1960 |teams=AAFC Brooklyn Dodgers AAFC Chicago\nHornets NFL Baltimore Colts NFL Washington Redskins NFL San\nFrancisco 49ers NFL Chicago Cardinals AFL Denver Broncos }} 'Hardy\nBrown' (May 8, 1924 â€“ November 8, 1991) was an American football\nlinebacker in the National Football League, All-America Football Conference, and\nthe American Football League. He played college football at the University of\nTulsa and then professionally for the San Francisco 49ers, Washington Redskins,\nand the Denver Broncos. He was one of only two men who played in the All-America\nFootball Conference, the National Football League, and the American Football\nLeague. Giants Among Men, Jack Cavanaugh, p. 54, 2008, Random House, ISBN\n978-1-4000-6717-6 (The other was Ben Agajanian.)\n\nWhen Brown was four years old, he witnessed the murder of his father. He was\nthen sent, along with his brothers and sisters, to live at the Texas Masonic\nHome, an orphanage for the children of deceased Freemasons in Fort Worth, Texas.\nAt the Masonic Home, Brown became friends with Tex Coulter. Giants Among\nMen, Jack Cavanaugh, p.52, 2008, Random House, ISBN 978-1-4000-6717-6\nBrown was a standout football player for the Mighty Mites, leading them to the\nstate semi-finals his senior year. He then briefly enlisted in the U. S. Army\nbefore playing football at Tulsa and eventually in the NFL. Brown became known\nas one of the roughest defensive players in the game, knocking out numerous\nopponents with his trademark shoulder push. The Rams once offered a bounty to\nany player who could take him out, and he had his shoulder pads checked before a\ngame once to make sure he did not have metal plating or other such material\nstuffed in them.\n\nBrown died in 1991 at a mental institution. Giants Among Men, Jack\nCavanaugh, p. 54, 2008, Random House, ISBN 978-1-4000-6717-6\n\nHardy Brown is featured prominently in the book, \"Twelve Mighty Orphans: The\nInspiring True Story of the Mighty Mites Who Ruled Texas Football\" by Jim Dent.\n","linknr":288,"url":"Hardy_Brown","recorded":1375056711,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Hardy_Brown&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Hardy_Brown&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Childress,_Texas","/wiki/American_football_positions","/wiki/Linebacker","/wiki/College_football","/wiki/University_of_Tulsa","/wiki/National_Football_League_Draft","/wiki/1947_NFL_Draft","/wiki/New_York_Giants","/wiki/Pro_Bowl","http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/BrowHa00.htm","http://www.nfl.com/players/profile?id=BRO469200","http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=BROWNHAR01","/wiki/1950_NFL_season","/wiki/1950_NFL_season","/wiki/1951_NFL_season","/wiki/1955_NFL_season","/wiki/1956_NFL_season","/wiki/1960_AFL_season","/wiki/All-America_Football_Conference","/wiki/B